	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Price volatility is likely to plague cocoa market</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the bank ABN Amro, the slowdown in consumption growth, in the light of the implementation of austerity measures, mean that ‘cocoa prices are at risk of “precipitous collapse” if prospects for supplies improve further’. The bank has raised its forecast for the cocoa surplus in 2010–11 by nearly half, to 227,000 tonnes. This follows an ‘extremely good season’ in Ghana and Côte d’Ivoire, the world’s biggest producers. The resolution of the political crisis in Côte d’Ivoire has seen a 24% increase in the volume of cocoa delivered to the ports for export.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Cocoa prices at risk of precipitous collapse’, 22 July 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/cocoa-prices-at-risk-of-precipitous-collapse--3388.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/cocoa-prices-at-risk-of-precipitous-collap...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>After price increases related to the political crisis in Côte d’Ivoire, it now appears that the growing surplus could lead to a sharp price decline, followed by a possible recovery if a deficit emerges in 2011/12. A critical question for West African states is how to effectively manage this price volatility. This needs to be addressed at two levels: state revenues and producer revenues.</p><p>In terms of state revenues, three possible areas of action can be identified. The first is diversification of the economy into other economic activities or by moving up the cocoa value chain. This type of action is particularly important in countries such as Côte d’Ivoire, where the cocoa sector accounts for 40% of export receipts, 20% of GDP, employs 600,000 producers and generates benefits for around 6 million people. Some progress is already apparent in terms of moving up the value chain in Côte d’Ivoire, where Barry Callebaut has recently announced a 70,000 tonne extension to its existing value-added processing facilities.</p><p>The second area for possible action is establishing a mechanism to smooth out revenues on a multi-annual basis, in what is traditionally a highly volatile commodity. This would amount to a renewal of some scheme along the lines of STABEX. Such an arrangement could be financed by:</p><p>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; international donor support;</p><p>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; some type of West African regional fund (Côte d’Ivoire, Ghana, Togo, Nigeria, Cameroon and Guinea are all cocoa producing countries); or</p><p>c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; an international fund financed by a levy on cocoa transactions on international futures markets.</p><p>The third area of action at the state level would involve cocoa exporting governments in supporting investment by taking a stake in international companies involved in downstream activities up to the final consumer such as ADM, Nestlé, Barry Callebaut etc. This would allow producing countries to benefit from upstream and retail activities (where the largest value in the cocoa chain resides) and to reduce their vulnerability to the volatile future markets.</p><p>In terms of producer revenues, given the importance of cocoa to the social fabric in a number of West African countries, it is apparent that the issue of revenue volatility cannot simply be left to the whims of futures markets, if the production base of the cocoa sector is not to be periodically undermined. In this context, the success enjoyed under the Ghanaian fixed season-long, producer price system is noteworthy. This has seen production reach nearly 1 million tonnes (even taking into account smuggling from Côte d’Ivoire). If such a fixed pricing system could be agreed regionally, it would not only serve to reduce smuggling, but would also strengthen the position of producers in negotiating crop pre-financing loans. It could even bring benefits in terms of negotiations around the transportation and marketing of cocoa beans.</p><p>Moving towards such an arrangement would appear to be consistent with calls from G20 agriculture ministers for a ‘market-based risk management tool-box that reduces household and community vulnerability to economic and climatic shocks’ and the call for ‘better predictability in the agricultural value chain’, via the establishment of formal contractual relationships between producers and processors.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
